ladders.explanation:
This sub-routine adapts standard binary search to find where a target value would be inserted in a sorted array, which corresponds to finding the leftmost or rightmost occurrence. The intuition is that instead of stopping when we find the target, we continue searching in one direction to find the boundary. For leftmost insertion, we want the first position where the element is >= target. For rightmost insertion, we want the last position where the element is <= target. This is achieved by modifying the comparison and update rules. For leftmost: when nums[mid] >= target, we set right = mid (continue searching left), otherwise left = mid + 1. This biases the search toward the left boundary. For rightmost: when nums[mid] <= target, we set left = mid (continue searching right), otherwise right = mid - 1. The ceiling division for mid in rightmost search prevents infinite loops. This sub-routine is the core of the full solution, used twice with different conditions. Common mistakes include using floor vs ceiling division incorrectly, not handling the final position check, and infinite loops when left and right are adjacent. Time complexity is O(log n), space is O(1).

Pseudocode for leftmost:
function findLeft(nums, target):
    left = 0
    right = len(nums) - 1
    while left < right:
        mid = left + (right - left) // 2
        if nums[mid] >= target:
            right = mid
        else:
            left = mid + 1
    return left

Pseudocode for rightmost:
function findRight(nums, target):
    left = 0
    right = len(nums) - 1
    while left < right:
        mid = left + (right - left + 1) // 2  # Ceiling
        if nums[mid] <= target:
            left = mid
        else:
            right = mid - 1
    return left

Time: O(log n)
Space: O(1)

Binary search is the fundamental algorithm that enables efficient searching in sorted arrays by repeatedly dividing the search interval in half. The intuition is that because the array is sorted, we can compare the middle element with our target and eliminate half of the remaining elements based on whether the target is less than or greater than the middle element. This gives us O(log n) time complexity compared to O(n) for linear search. The algorithm maintains two pointers: left (start of search interval) and right (end). We calculate mid = left + (right - left) // 2 to avoid overflow. If nums[mid] == target, we found it and return mid. If target < nums[mid], we search left half by setting right = mid - 1. If target > nums[mid], we search right half by setting left = mid + 1. We continue until left > right, indicating target not found. Common mistakes include off-by-one errors in the while condition (should be left <= right for existence check), integer overflow when calculating mid (use left + (right-left)//2 instead of (left+right)//2), and not returning -1 when not found. This building block is essential for L2 because the modified binary searches for boundaries build upon this standard pattern by changing the comparison and update rules.

Pseudocode:
function binarySearch(nums, target):
    left = 0
    right = len(nums) - 1
    while left <= right:
        mid = left + (right - left) // 2
        if nums[mid] == target:
            return mid
        elif target < nums[mid]:
            right = mid - 1
        else:
            left = mid + 1
    return -1

Time: O(log n)
Space: O(1)
